reviewText: I was sooooo shocked to see this movie finally arrive on DVD after all this time. This movie is pure 80's FUN! I have been waiting for this movie to arrive on DVD ever since the 80's ended. If anyone is down or needs a good laugh then this is the movie to watch. Rebecca and Mary Gross have excellent comedic timing, especially Gross. She says some of the most random things that are way out in left field and it does nothing but evoke laughter.Rebecca & Mary are 2 field trainees attending school to become FBI agents. Rebecca is street smart and physically trained while Mary is a bookworm, but doesn't have the EDGE she needs to make it all the way. These two women are two halves that complete one another and form a bond as roommates. This movie is complete laughter from start to finish and goes at a great pace. Sometimes i am shocked at how quickly it ends. The price tag is a bit hefty on Amazon, but pick up this DVD. It's a total winner.
summary: CLASSIC! A movie one can watch over & over

reviewText: This flick is passable entertainment that meanders between the mundane to the mediocre.  Like a Chinese meal it's forgotten after you've digested it.  It purports to be a comedy but there aren't many laughs to be found here.  Allegedly the makers had the full cooperation of the FBI and therein lies the double-edged sword.  The depiction of the Bureau's training program feels authentic and informative, however, the film isn't very forthcoming about the warts in the agency.  The film's saving grace is the terrific rapport between Rebecca DeMornay and Mary Gross whose efforts keep the enterprise afloat.  A good performance is also offered here by Fred Thompson as the supervisor of the training program whom I would have voted for President if he had the stomach for it.  This is an OK flick but it's certainly not worth it's prohibitive list price.
summary: Wally George's Daughter And Michael Gross' Sister

reviewText: FEDS is better than Wildcats (which I also just saw again), but not much better. Here is yet another outdated Warner Bros. movie where it's apparently hilarious to think of women in a field previously predominately occupied by men.. HIL-ARIOUS.. Like Wildcats (from '86), FEDS relies on now forgotten stereotypes and predictable plot points to move the mundane film along, with an outcome that's as easy to see as De Mornay's blonde hair... Women want to bed a fed .. women gets laughed at by men.. women study really hard to be a feds.. practices training.. men not laugh anymore.. The End..I saw this again for the first time in over 20 years.. and I have to say, it's another 80's film to demonstrate why 80's isn't so classic after all, and just like the bad clothes and the ratted hair..and sometimes the music, it should be left right where it was... Both films are from Warner Bros..and it's hard to believe with all the worthless junk they churned out in the 80's and 90's, how they haven't gone totally broke.. Oh wait, they did at one point..De Mornay's best work is still "The Hand That Rocks the Cradle" (1991), but that wasn't Warner Bros., it was Disney's Hollywood Pictures...
summary: Meh.. It's typical mundane Warner Bros. junk from the 80's

reviewText: Ivan Reitman has directed both Ghostbuster movies but decides to try something different.  And I say this one is a good one!  Rebecca DeMornay (Hand That Rocks The Cradle, Risky Business), Mary Gross (Hot To Trot) star in this bumbling comedy about two women who beat the system and decide to become FBI agents amongst men.  DeWitt (DeMornay) who just got out of the Army, goes to D.C. to become an FBI agent, and when she gets there, she meets Janet Zuckermann (Gross) they start off stale but as they advance, they become the best of friends.  Zuckermann gets stepped on from time to time cause they feel she can't cut it, until she finally takes up for herself.  Sen. Fred Dalton Thompson of Tennessee stars in this he had also been in another movie DIE HARD 2 with Bruce Willis, in this he plays Bulleki the headmaster of the FBI School.  Things get more exciting when they do the field exam where Bulleki plays a terrorist and kidnaps the professor and the students have to rescue them in order to get their badges and certificates to pass.  DeWitt and Zuckermann pass and get L.A.  I think this movie is kinda weird at first but, it has some funny parts halfway.  I hope that Warner Home Video puts it out on DVD cause I would definitely buy this one too!

reviewText: Feds was a bit of a disappointment considering the presence of one of the most attractive women of all time (no exaggeration here!!!).A young female US Marine decides to try her luck with the FBI so she applies and gets accepted to the FBI Academy.  In a very predictable manner reminiscent of Police Academy, but without the humor or the sex, she struggles to get past the hurdles laid before her.In short, the acting is pretty bad, the setting is not noteworthy, the humor is just not there (at all), the music is poor at best, while the plot and the dialogues are average and way "below average" respectively.It seems as though the actors/writers/directors/producers met up with each other at a hotel lounge over drinks, and then decided, on the spot, to make a quick and easy film to keep themselves busy while waiting for a good break.In a nutshell, it's a mediocre movie and that's about it; no masterpiece here...  1.5 StarsIf it's a Rebecca DeMornay movie that you're looking for, try the AMAZING 1992 thriller The Hand that Rocks the Cradle.  You won't be disappointed!
summary: Rebecca is two Stars, and... that's it!

reviewText: Rebecca DeMornay and Mary Gross make a wonderful team in this hilarious movie.  I saw it for the first time when I was stressed out from collge studies and working almost full time.It's about two young women who want to be FBI agents and are struggling with all the demands.  Mary Gross' character (Janet Zuckerman) is a "brainy" gal who is long on study skills and short on athletic know-how.  Rebecca DeMornay's character (Ellie DeWitt) is just the opposite--long on athletic abilities, but inexperienced in the academic department.  The teaming up of these two like-minded but opposite people is, in my opinion, "buddy action" at its best.I still pull this movie out and watch it.  I'm always impressed with Ms. DeMornay's awesome acting ability and Ms. Gross' comedy skills.  It's a great "escape" when I feel stressed out.
summary: Fun to watch, and completely entertaining

reviewText: PLOT: 2 women are accepted in to the male dominated FBI~ opposites bookish Janice and ex marine Ellie become partners ..fun~Now the FBI is accepting women~ former Marine Ellie (pretty Rebecca De Mornay) and bookish smart Janice (Mary Gross) apply and are accepted~ soon the 2 opposites are needing each other to survive~ Ellie shows Janice self defense and brainey Janice shows Ellie how to study and learn~ the fun is how the ladies survive the male dominated and chauvenistic treatment BY the guys~ as the class gets smaller and smaller due to cuts from bad grades and poor field perfomance the ladies still are there~ From tracking down clues the attesting  BIG male criminals we have fun~ a lot of FBI puns and humor~ the Ending IS clever~ I give this one a solid 8 OUT OF 10 FOR SILLY FBI puns and gender humor~(male vs female)

reviewText: This movie is a favorite of mine, I lost the only copy I had of this movie to my ex-wife when I moved out so I had to order a brand new one from Amazon, it did not disappoint, Rebecca DeMornay delivers a terrific role as a marine turned wanna-be FBI agent.  Mary Gross as her bumbling partner and now presidential candidate Fred Thompson as their chief instructor.  The laughs come, however, not at a brisk pace but this is definitely one of those movies you can watch more than once just for the entertainment value. I whole-heartedly reccomend this movie.  The only reason it didn't get a 5th star was because it was NOT on DVD, which is a shame it hasn't been released that way as yet, perhaps someday.
summary: You have the right to be entertained.......
